"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[346],{1346:function(e,t,a){a.r(t),a.d(t,{SKELETON:function(){return o}});let o={id:"skeleton",title:"The Skeleton Pirate",shortDescription:"Definitely NOT a magically animated skeleton.",skillGrid:{exploration:["star","open","open","star","star","blocked","blocked"],brawn:["star","star","open","open","star","blocked","blocked"],hunting:["star","open","open","star","blocked","blocked","blocked"],aim:["star","open","star","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked"],swagger:["open","open","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked"],navigation:["star","star","open","star","blocked","blocked","blocked"]},constellation:a(9774).ub,storyBlanks:[{number:1,prompt:"A bone-related pun name",type:"text"},{number:2,prompt:"The pirate name of another player",type:"player_name"},{number:3,prompt:"An excuse for why you're so bony",type:"text"},{number:4,prompt:"Something skeletons definitely don't do",type:"text"},{number:5,prompt:"A type of hat that covers your face",type:"text"}],backstory:"I am a perfectly normal, living, breathing human person, and I would appreciate it if people would stop asking why my skin is transparent, my eyes are glowing, and my body appears to be made entirely of bones. It's a CONDITION. It's called {3}. Look it up. It's very real and very common and definitely not something I just made up.\n\nMy name is {1}, and I am NOT a magically animated skeleton. I eat food (it falls right through me, but that's the {3}), I sleep (with my eyes open, because of the {3}), and I definitely {4} like all normal humans do. See? Totally normal.\n\nI joined this pirate crew because they were the only ones who didn't immediately try to exorcise me or set me on fire. The captain took one look at me and said, \"We could use someone who doesn't need to eat.\" I explained that I DO eat, it just... passes through, and they said, \"Right. Welcome aboard.\" {2} is the only one who's caught on, but I've sworn them to secrecy. If word gets out that I'm a— that I MIGHT be perceived as a skeleton, the local clergy will be after me faster than you can say \"unholy abomination.\"\n\nI wear a {5} to cover my face in public and I try very hard to remember to breathe. I sometimes forget, and people find it unsettling when I don't breathe for forty-five minutes.",events:[{narrative:'I lost my left arm during a fight today. No blood, of course, because of the {3}. I just picked it up and stuck it back on. {2} stared at me for a very long time. "It\'s fine," I said. "Happens all the time. Very normal human thing." They did not seem convinced.',effect:"Re-roll +2. Infamy +1."},{narrative:'A necromancer we met at port recognized me for what I am — I mean, recognized that I have {3} — and offered me this artifact. He said it would help me "maintain my form." I don\'t know what that means because I am a normal human, but I took it anyway. It does make my bones — I mean, my BODY — feel stronger.',effect:"Retrieve card 77 Bone Ward Charm from the story deck."},{narrative:"The crew played music tonight and everyone danced. I danced too, because I am a normal human who {4}s. Unfortunately, my jaw fell off mid-dance. I claimed it was a party trick. {2} handed it back to me without a word. We have an understanding, {2} and I.",effect:"Crew +1. Discontent -1."},{narrative:"A group of children at the last port pointed at me and screamed \"SKELETON!\" I calmly explained that I have {3} and that it's very rude to point. Their mother apologized and gave me a scarf. I appreciate the gesture, though scarves don't help much when you don't have a neck. I mean, when your neck is very thin. Because of the {3}.",effect:"Re-roll +1. Swagger +1."},{narrative:"I sat on the bow tonight and watched the stars, and for a moment I tried to remember what it was like before — before the {3}, before the magic, before I woke up in a coffin with no memories and glowing eyes. Was I once alive? Did I have a family? All I know is what I am now: a pirate, a crewmate, and a definitely-not-a-skeleton. And maybe that's enough.",effect:"Gain 1 skill of your choice. Re-roll +2."}],endings:{bad:{threshold:"≤3",text:'Your secret is finally exposed when a priest boards the ship and immediately starts chanting exorcism rites. Your {5} blows off in the wind, revealing your distinctly skeletal face to the entire crew. "I HAVE {3}!" you scream, but it\'s too late. The priest\'s magic strips away the enchantment holding you together, and your bones clatter to the deck. {2} gathers your remains in a sack and buries you on a quiet island, marking the grave with a headstone that reads: "{1}. They definitely {4}ed. A very normal human." Your jaw, which {2} kept as a memento, continues to insist you have {3} whenever anyone picks it up.'},good:{threshold:"4",text:'You continue pirating for many years, your {3} excuse holding up surprisingly well. {2} becomes your best friend and fiercest protector, threatening to throw anyone overboard who asks too many questions about your... condition. You eventually retire to a small town where you become a beloved, if eccentric, figure. You wear your {5} everywhere and tell children stories about your adventures. The town doctor gives up trying to diagnose you after his third stethoscope detects no heartbeat. "Must be broken," you suggest helpfully. You live — or exist — happily, and when asked your age, you say "old enough to know better," which is technically true since you have no idea how old you are.'},legendary:{threshold:"5",text:"The truth about your condition is finally revealed — not by exposure, but by choice. When a dark sorcerer threatens the crew with an army of undead, you step forward and remove your {5}. \"I am {1},\" you declare, your bones glowing with ethereal light. \"And I am MORE than a skeleton.\" Drawing on the same magic that animates you, you command the sorcerer's army to stand down. They obey, recognizing you as one of their own — but stronger, willed, and free. The sorcerer is defeated, and the crew finally accepts you for what you are: undead, but more alive than most living people they know. {2} gives a speech declaring that you're the bravest person — living or otherwise — they've ever met. You finally stop pretending to breathe, and it's an enormous relief. You continue to insist you have {3}, but now it's an inside joke. Everyone laughs. Even your detachable jaw laughs."}}}}}]);